  "overall_strengths": [
    "Strong coverage for Android-specific intent/exported-component issues, especially old-school IPC abuse, nested-intent patterns, and intent-triggered crash conditions.",
    "Combines cheap heuristics and heavier interprocedural analyses in one pipeline, which is useful for triage.",
    "Externalized rule files make many checks easy to retune without code changes.",
    "Real interprocedural taint exists, and findings can include both source and sink plus an optional path.",
    "The tool directly consumes APKs and uses Soot/FlowDroid Jimple, so it works below source level."
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "Many categories are heuristic and can over-report badly:",
    "Custom `HostnameVerifier` flags any implementation",
    "`ZipEntry` flags mere type presence",
    "WebView password check only understands literal `false`",
    "WebView file-access check only catches literal `true`",
    "Default taint sources are narrow for inbound analysis: mostly intent-related APIs, not a broad Android privacy source model.",
    "Flow-out analysis is also narrow and appears aimed at password-like UI widgets; this is inferred from the code and FlowDroid layout settings, not explicitly encoded in the source/sink file.",
    "Reachability findings are weakly typed: they only say that a dangerous API is reachable, not whether it is attacker-controlled.",
    "Output lacks file path, source line, confidence, and module name.",
    "The score is ad hoc and uneven. The WebView file-access bitmask can produce disproportionately large scores.",
    "Several promising modules are not actually part of the main `vulnanalysis` command:",
    "`PendingIntentScanner` exists but is not called",
    "`DynamicReceiverFinder` is unfinished",
    "`ProviderURLFinder` is empty",
    "The project is dated. Default rules focus on Android 4.x/5.x era issues and old APIs such as `setSavePassword`.",
    "Taint relevance:",
    "Medium",
    "Reason: JAADAS does contain genuine interprocedural taint analysis and custom intent-taint logic, but only one part of the tool uses it, and the default source model is fairly narrow. For a Tool Prior schema, taint capability should be recorded as real but specialized, not as a broad general-purpose taint engine."
  ],
